	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0023">23<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0023.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">
      
      <h1>From Matthew Ridley</h1>
      <div class="docbody">
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Dear Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Paris February the 10. 1784</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I am honored with yours of the 25<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">th:</span> Ult<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">o.</span> You will perhaps have heard by other hands the heavey loss I have met with M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">rs.</span> Ridley died the 21<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">st.</span> Ult<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">o.</span> I am highly sensible of your kind wishes If the kind concern of Friends &amp; the sincere Prayers of an Affectionate Husband could have averted the Event I had still been blessd with her! Itis a Subject I must drop. Thank God! my Son Essex is in good Health.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">What the Roman in Heaven may think of the use made of his Name &amp; plough I know not? But certain itis that many on Earth who may not possess all the stiff Virtue of a Cincinnatus think that both his Name &amp; plough are strangely abused. Officers, serving under an Absolute Monarch &amp; whose elevations depend on Wars and Broils, arranging themselves under the revered Name of Cincinnatus!preposterous Idea!; And is I think only to be equalled by the permission given to them to carry at the Same Button Hole, with the Decoration of a King the Golden trinket of a set of Individuals assuming to themselves the power of creating dinctinctions hitherto unknown to themselves or Fellow Citizens I cannot say who was the Inventor, but that the Idea is French I have no doubt, none but
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0024">[24<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0024.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
such could have imagined a Bit of Ribon with a Trinket at the End of it to make one Citizen contemn the other.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I hope &amp; believe our Officers have not weighd the tendency of this BusinessPity itis that some one of Influence had not stopd it in timeAfter decorating the French Officers with it by Permission of the King I fear every <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Chevalier</span> will be too tenacious of the distinction to relinquish itThe only mode I know to succeed in this would be <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Ridicule</span> &amp; that of the most pointed kind both here and in AmericaThe difficulty will be how to convey the Ridicule properly into this Country. Otherwise one might say to a <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Chevalier of the Royal Order.</span> Le Ruban que vous portez nest pas grande chose Aujourdhui Celui dune societ des Individus est attach a la meme Boutonniere par parmission de Votre Roi et consequemment les Particuliers sont en Etat de confuer de distinctions aufin eclatantes &amp; honorables que votre Saint Roi Louis. Nous avons plusieurs Ordres en AmeriqueLes Francs Maons, Les fils de S<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">t.</span> Patrick Les fils de S<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">t.</span> Andrew et Les fils de S<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">t.</span> Tamminy (Roi Indien) On dit que tous ces Ordres ont intention denvoyer un de Leur societ en France pour solicite la permission du Roi que tous les Officiers Francois sans distinction puissent porter LEmbleme de leur Ordre. Quel Bonheur pour ceux qui ont si long temps soupir pour un Morceau de Ruban. Allors mon Ami, Courage vous ne serez pas oubli, et jespere quon ne tardera pas dy adjouter un Collet<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">de Chervre.pour ceux qui ont le Manie des Rubans.</span>[<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;"></span>]<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0003" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I am sorry indeed for what you tell me about M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r.</span> Morriss BillsStill I hope something will be done about them for I dread the Event of their going back.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The late Loan here for 100 Millions is quite filled &amp; upon the same terms they might I believe have had as much more. Every thing seems quiet&amp; it is said the differences between Russia &amp; the Porte are settled.Confusion I hear prevails in England &amp; indeed it appears they take great pains there to create disorder.</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The Doctors complaint continues much the samenot very troublesome.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0004" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r</span> Grand &amp; Family well as are all your FriendsM<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r</span> Jay has been returned about a Fortnight</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">With the Money you left I paid your Appartments. $744.Letters received at sundry times $78.15 &amp; the remainder I have paid to M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r</span> Barclay whom you will please to call upon for it amounting $377.15</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The packet that carried out M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r.</span> Thaxter is returned but has brought very few Letters.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0005" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> A Vessel is arrived in London left
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0025">[25<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0025.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
Annapolis the 6<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">th.</span> of January. The Members of Congress excepting the President were there. As the Captain got under sail he heard the Guns fire &amp; therefore supposes he was arrived &amp; that a House was made up</p>
        <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Remember me kindly to your Son M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">rs.</span> Barclay &amp; Family are well &amp; join in best wishes I am with Respect D<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r</span> Sir / Y<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r.</span> m<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">o</span> Obed<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">t</span> Serv<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">t</span></p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed">Matt: Ridley</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docback">
        <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-sn">
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>); internal address: His Exc<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">y:</span> J. Adams.; endorsed: M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r</span> Ridley Feb. 10 / 1784.</p>

        </div>
        <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0001">1</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">In his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0228" class="document">letter of 25 Jan.</a>, <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> wrote, I still hope, M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">rs</span> Ridley will recover, and closed with a request to be remembered to M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">rs</span> Ridley and the Children. Adding to Ridleys grief was the death on 8 Jan. of his four-month-old son, Lucius Lloyd. Ann Richardson Ridley had been ill since giving birth to Lucius in Sept. 1783 (vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0090#ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0206" class="pageNo">15:206</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0227%20ADMS-print-06-15-02-0228#ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0468" class="pageNo">468469</a>).</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0002">2</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">For Ridleys earlier comments about the Society of the Cincinnati and its activities in France, see his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0212" class="document">letter of 27 Dec.</a>, vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0211%20ADMS-print-06-15-02-0212#ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0436" class="pageNo">15:436438</a>. The societys French branch held its first meeting at Paris on 7 Jan. 1784. <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> had been equally critical of the society in <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0228" class="document">his reply of 25 Jan.</a>, but see also the <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0046" class="document">8 March letter from the Marquis de Lafayette</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0064" class="document"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s reply of the 28th</a>, both below.</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0003-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0003">3</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The ribbon you wear is no great thing these days. That from a society of individuals is fixed to the same buttonhole with the permission of your king, and consequently private individuals are able to confer distinctions as dazzling and as honorable as your holy King Louis. We have several orders in America: the Freemasons, the Sons of St. Patrick, the Sons of St. Andrew, and the Sons of St. Tammany (Indian king). They say that each of these orders intends to send one of its members to France to ask the king for permission to have all French officers regardless of their rank be able to wear its emblem. What happiness for those who have sighed for so long to have a bit of ribbon! So, my friend, courage. You will not be forgotten, and I hope they will not be long in adding a collar <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">of chevrons for those with a mania for ribbons.</span></p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0004-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0004">4</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">In his 27 Jan. letter, <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> had inquired about Benjamin Franklins Complaint of the Stone, Gravel &amp;c (vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0228#ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0469" class="pageNo">15:469</a>).</p>

        </div>

        <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0005-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0015-fn-0005">5</a>
          
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Courier de lEurope</span> (vol. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-15-02-0148%20ADMS-print-06-15-02-0149%20ADMS-print-06-15-02-0150#ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0306" class="pageNo">15:306</a>).</p>

        </div>

      </div>
